# Git closeout after implementation

When you **edit tracked project files** (code, config, or rules) to satisfy **this user’s active request**, treating the task as “done” **without** updating the remote wastes their time on the next machine or deploy.

## Required before you end your turn

1. Run **`git status`** in the repo root.
2. If there are **meaningful uncommitted changes** (not only editor noise the user will discard):
   - **`git add`** the files that belong to the request.
   - **`git commit`** with a clear message (full sentences).
   - **`git push`** to the current branch’s upstream (e.g. `origin/master`). If push fails, say so and paste the error; do **not** imply the change is on GitHub.

## When this does *not* apply

- The user **explicitly** asked to keep changes local, skip commit, or skip push.
- You only **read** files or ran **read-only** diagnostics and made **no** edits.

## Why

Local edits are not “the project” until they are **committed and pushed**. Cursor user rules are easy to miss after long tool runs; this file is **in-repo** so agents working in this workspace see it every session.
